Chapter 1. Admin Guide

1.1. Overview

   The rust_http_webhook module provides fire-and-forget HTTP POST
   webhook delivery for SIP event payloads. Script functions return
   immediately while delivery happens asynchronously in a background
   tokio task within each worker process.

   This module is useful for pushing SIP event data to external
   systems (CDR collectors, fraud detection, real-time analytics)
   without blocking SIP message processing. If the internal queue
   is full, payloads are silently dropped and a counter is
   incremented.

1.2. How it works

   Each OpenSIPS worker process maintains its own independent
   fire-and-forget HTTP dispatcher backed by a tokio runtime. When
   rust_webhook() is called from the script, the payload string is
   enqueued into a bounded channel. A background task dequeues
   payloads and sends them as HTTP POST requests to the configured
   URL.

   If the queue is full (exceeds max_queue), the payload is dropped
   and the internal drop counter is incremented. The script function
   always returns 1 (success) unless the dispatcher is not
   initialized.

   The HTTP client respects the configured timeout and content type.
   For HTTPS endpoints, a custom CA certificate file can be
   specified via tls_ca_file.

1.3. Dependencies

1.3.1. OpenSIPS Modules

   The following modules must be loaded before this module:
     * None.

1.3.2. External Libraries or Applications

   The following libraries or applications must be installed
   before running OpenSIPS with this module loaded:
     * None. All HTTP functionality is compiled into the Rust
       shared library.

1.4. Exported Parameters

1.4.1. url (string)

   The HTTP(S) endpoint URL where webhook payloads are POSTed.
   This parameter is required. The module will fail to load if
   this parameter is not set.

   Default value is "None" (must be set).

   Example 1.1. Set url parameter
...
modparam("rust_http_webhook", "url", "https://example.com/hook")
...

1.4.2. max_queue (integer)

   Maximum number of payloads that can be queued per worker process
   before new payloads are dropped. Each worker maintains its own
   independent queue.

   Default value is "1000".

   Example 1.2. Set max_queue parameter
...
modparam("rust_http_webhook", "max_queue", 2000)
...

1.4.3. http_timeout (integer)

   HTTP request timeout in seconds. Requests that exceed this
   timeout are abandoned.

   Default value is "5".

   Example 1.3. Set http_timeout parameter
...
modparam("rust_http_webhook", "http_timeout", 10)
...

1.4.4. content_type (string)

   The Content-Type header value sent with each POST request.

   Default value is "application/json".

   Example 1.4. Set content_type parameter
...
modparam("rust_http_webhook", "content_type", "application/x-ndjson")
...

1.4.5. tls_ca_file (string)

   Path to a custom CA certificate file (PEM format) for TLS
   verification of the webhook endpoint. If not set, the system
   default CA bundle is used.

   Default value is "None" (system defaults).

   Example 1.5. Set tls_ca_file parameter
...
modparam("rust_http_webhook", "tls_ca_file", "/etc/ssl/certs/custom-ca.pem")
...

1.5. Exported Functions

1.5.1. rust_webhook(payload)

   Enqueue a payload string for asynchronous HTTP POST delivery to
   the configured webhook URL. The function returns immediately
   without waiting for the HTTP request to complete.

   If the per-worker queue is full, the payload is silently dropped
   and a warning is logged.

   Parameters:
     * payload (string) - The payload body to POST. Typically a
       JSON string constructed using pseudo-variables. This
       parameter is mandatory.

   Return values:
     * 1 - payload enqueued (or dropped due to full queue)
     * -1 - error (missing parameter or dispatcher not initialized)

   This function can be used from REQUEST_ROUTE, FAILURE_ROUTE,
   and ONREPLY_ROUTE.

   Example 1.6. rust_webhook usage
...
route {
    rust_webhook("{\"method\":\"$rm\",\"from\":\"$fu\",\"ruri\":\"$ru\"}");
}
...

   Example 1.7. Complete opensips.cfg example
...
loadmodule "rust_http_webhook.so"

modparam("rust_http_webhook", "url", "https://analytics.example.com/sip-events")
modparam("rust_http_webhook", "max_queue", 2000)
modparam("rust_http_webhook", "http_timeout", 5)
modparam("rust_http_webhook", "content_type", "application/json")

route {
    # Send a webhook for every INVITE
    if (is_method("INVITE")) {
        rust_webhook("{\"event\":\"call\",\"method\":\"$rm\",\"from\":\"$fu\",\"to\":\"$tu\",\"callid\":\"$ci\",\"src_ip\":\"$si\"}");
    }

    # Send a webhook for REGISTERs
    if (is_method("REGISTER")) {
        rust_webhook("{\"event\":\"register\",\"contact\":\"$ct\",\"from\":\"$fu\",\"expires\":\"$hdr(Expires)\"}");
    }
}
...
